=========================================
MOST ASKED STL INTERVIEW QUESTIONS & ANSWERS
=========================================

=========================================
1. GENERAL STL QUESTIONS
=========================================

Q1. What is STL in C++?
-----------------------------------------
A:
STL (Standard Template Library) is a collection of template-based classes and functions
that provide common data structures and algorithms like vector, map, set, stack, queue, etc.

-----------------------------------------

Q2. What are components of STL?
-----------------------------------------
A:
1. Containers (vector, list, map, set, etc.)
2. Algorithms (sort, find, count, etc.)
3. Iterators (connect containers and algorithms)

-----------------------------------------

Q3. Why is STL used?
-----------------------------------------
A:
- Saves development time
- Highly optimized implementation
- Reduces code complexity
- Reusable components

=========================================
2. VECTOR QUESTIONS
=========================================

Q1. Why is vector called dynamic array?
-----------------------------------------
A:
Because it automatically resizes itself when capacity is full.

-----------------------------------------

Q2. Difference between vector and array?
-----------------------------------------
A:
vector:
- dynamic size
- heap memory
- resizable

array:
- fixed size
- stack/heap
- not resizable

-----------------------------------------

Q3. What happens when vector grows?
-----------------------------------------
A:
- New larger memory allocated
- Elements copied to new memory
- Old memory freed
Time complexity = O(n)

-----------------------------------------

Q4. Why is push_back amortized O(1)?
-----------------------------------------
A:
Because resizing happens occasionally, but most insertions are O(1).

=========================================
3. MAP / UNORDERED_MAP
=========================================

Q1. Difference between map and unordered_map?
-----------------------------------------
A:
map:
- Red-black tree
- O(log n)
- sorted keys

unordered_map:
- hash table
- O(1) average
- no order

-----------------------------------------

Q2. Why is unordered_map faster?
-----------------------------------------
A:
Because it uses hashing instead of tree traversal.

-----------------------------------------

Q3. Worst case of unordered_map?
-----------------------------------------
A:
O(n) due to hash collisions.

-----------------------------------------

Q4. When to use map?
-----------------------------------------
A:
- Need sorted keys
- Need range queries (lower_bound, upper_bound)

=========================================
4. SET QUESTIONS
=========================================

Q1. Difference between set and unordered_set?
-----------------------------------------
A:
set:
- ordered (tree)
- O(log n)

unordered_set:
- hash table
- O(1) average

-----------------------------------------

Q2. Does set allow duplicates?
-----------------------------------------
A:
No, set stores only unique elements.

-----------------------------------------

Q3. Difference between set and multiset?
-----------------------------------------
A:
set → unique elements
multiset → allows duplicates

=========================================
5. LIST / VECTOR / DEQUE
=========================================

Q1. Difference between vector, list, deque?
-----------------------------------------
A:
vector:
- contiguous memory
- fast traversal

list:
- doubly linked list
- fast insertion/deletion in middle

deque:
- multiple blocks
- fast front + back operations

-----------------------------------------

Q2. Why list is slower in practice?
-----------------------------------------
A:
Due to poor cache locality.

=========================================
6. STACK / QUEUE / PRIORITY_QUEUE
=========================================

Q1. Difference between stack and queue?
-----------------------------------------
A:
stack → LIFO
queue → FIFO

-----------------------------------------

Q2. Why is deque default container?
-----------------------------------------
A:
Because it supports both front and back operations efficiently in O(1).

-----------------------------------------

Q3. Why priority_queue is called heap?
-----------------------------------------
A:
Because internally it is implemented using a binary heap.

-----------------------------------------

Q4. Complexity of priority_queue?
-----------------------------------------
A:
push → O(log n)
pop → O(log n)
top → O(1)

=========================================
7. ITERATORS
=========================================

Q1. What is iterator?
-----------------------------------------
A:
An object that points to elements in a container and allows traversal.

-----------------------------------------

Q2. Types of iterators?
-----------------------------------------
A:
1. Input iterator
2. Output iterator
3. Forward iterator
4. Bidirectional iterator
5. Random access iterator

-----------------------------------------

Q3. Which containers support random access iterators?
-----------------------------------------
A:
vector, deque, array

=========================================
8. PAIR QUESTIONS
=========================================

Q1. What is pair?
-----------------------------------------
A:
A container that stores two values together.

Example:
pair<int,int> p = {1,2};

-----------------------------------------

Q2. Where is pair used?
-----------------------------------------
A:
- map (key-value)
- graph edges
- returning multiple values

=========================================
9. IMPORTANT REAL INTERVIEW QUESTIONS
=========================================

Q1. Why is vector preferred over list?
-----------------------------------------
A:
Because vector has better cache locality and faster traversal.

-----------------------------------------

Q2. Why is unordered_map not always used?
-----------------------------------------
A:
Because worst case becomes O(n) due to collisions.

-----------------------------------------

Q3. Why does map keep elements sorted?
-----------------------------------------
A:
Because it uses a balanced BST (Red-Black Tree).

-----------------------------------------

Q4. Why is priority_queue used?
-----------------------------------------
A:
To always access max/min element efficiently.

-----------------------------------------

Q5. Why STL is important in interviews?
-----------------------------------------
A:
It helps solve problems quickly with optimized implementations.

